prevent referral failures from blocking settlement. Let me check what the spec actually requires about this behavior.\n\nThe spec is explicit—System Invariant 4 and FR-10 both demand atomicity: the referral earning insert must happen in the same transaction as the settlement write. This means if either fails, both should roll back and retry together. The real issue is that if a referral constraint fails, it could block game settlement, but that's actually the correct behavior to avoid half-committed states. So I need to remove the try/catch wrapper around `recordReferralEarnings` to let failures propagate and trigger a full transaction rollback.\n\nThe challenge is that `recordReferralEarnings` is designed to be resilient, so throwing errors could cause repeated settlement retries if there's a persistent referral data issue. The pragmatic solution is to use `ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING` in the insert statement to handle duplicate keys gracefully, while letting other errors bubble up and cause the transaction to roll back. This way, duplicate key conflicts don't block settlement, but genuine data issues still trigger a retry.\n\nWriting the conflict handling... I'm reconsidering whether I even need to add `withTransaction` to the Db interface at all—I could instead inject the raw `sql` connection into `SettleTxDeps` and call `sql.begin()` directly within the settlement functions, which would be simpler than refactoring the interface.\n\nBut that won't work because the `db` methods need access to the transaction connection, not a separate one. So the `withTransaction` approach on Db is the right path forward.\n\nI'm checking what dependencies are currently available in `SettleTxDeps` to see if there's a simpler way to handle this.\n\nSince `sql` isn't available in the deps and adding it would mean duplicating the writes in raw SQL, I'll go ahead with implementing `withTransaction` on the Db interface. My plan is to add the method signature to the Db interface, then modify the `createDb` function to support transaction injection...\n\nImplementing the interface changes... I'm wrestling with the type casting here — the `null as unknown as ReferralEarning` pattern feels hacky. Since `recordReferralEarnings` doesn't actually use the return value and the conflict scenario is virtually impossible within a transaction, I think I'll just leave `insertReferralEarning` unchanged and rely on the existing error handling to catch any edge cases.\n\nMy implementation plan is straightforward: add `withTransaction` to the Db interface, modify `createDb` to accept injected sql, implement the transaction wrapper, and guard the `close()` method. Then I'll wrap the settlement writes in both coinflip and lord settlement handlers with `db.withTransaction()`.\n\nOne thing I'm noticing though — in `recordReferralEarnings`, duplicate key errors are being caught and silently absorbed...\n\nChecking how postgres.js handles transaction failures...\n\nWhen a query fails inside the transaction callback, postgres.js catches the error and issues a ROLLBACK, rejecting the promise. But if I catch the error myself with try/catch, postgres.js might not realize the transaction is in an aborted state — it'll attempt to COMMIT, which fails, forcing a ROLLBACK instead. The key question is whether postgres.js tracks the transaction state internally or relies on the callback throwing to signal failure.\n\nEither way, the `sql.begin()` promise rejects because the COMMIT fails, which means the entire settlement fails and retries — and that's actually correct per the spec's requirement that referral earnings and settlement be atomic. The original try/catch was meant to prevent referral failures from blocking settlement, but the spec explicitly demands atomicity, so this behavior change is intentional. I should probably remove the error handling from `recordReferralEarnings` to make this clearer. I'm tracing through how postgres.js handles caught errors within a transaction — even if we catch the error in JavaScript, PostgreSQL marks the transaction as aborted, so any subsequent commands fail until we explicitly rollback, which postgres.js does automatically and rejects the begin() promise. This means settleMatch will throw and the retry logic will catch it, which is exactly what we want since a rolled-back transaction means the duplicate row never persisted. I'm satisfied this approach works, so I'll move forward with the implementation.\n\nNow I'm laying out the specific changes needed: adding a withTransaction method to the Db interface that wraps database operations, modifying createDb to accept injected sql, and then using this wrapper in settleMatch and settleLordRound to ensure those critical sections run atomically. Let me start writing the code.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":8834,"cache_read_input_tokens":72841,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":8834},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b75d7aec-4dd6-4c16-a100-27ad57796fa9","uuid":"d9c5b499-2f5d-43e6-9c15-f9aba7283175"}
